<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Calls for Emergency Aid to S. Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. World Food Program (WFP)
Friday calls for urgently funding needed airdrops of food aid to
victims of war and drought in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The airdrops will be part of a 65.8 million U.S. Dollars
operation starting the day to deliver 83,000 tons of food to 2.48
million Sudanese facing famine over the next 12 months, said the
WFP in a news release Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is extremely serious in southern Sudan where
the combined effects of insecurity, drought and floods have
caused widespread crop failure," said the Rome-headquartered
body.
</P>
<P>
"Up to 200,000 people in northern Sudan also need aid because
of chronic shortages due to drought," it continued.
</P>
<P>
Food deficits of 30 to 60 percent are expected in Bahr el
Ghazal and Eastern Equatorial in the south, South Kordofan and
North Darfur in the north and displaced persons camps around Wau
in the south and the capital Khartoum, said the WFP.
</P>
<P>
The long civil war and repeated restrictions of access and
aircraft clearances in the past few months by authorities have
hampered attempts to reach the hungry, said WFP.
</P>
<P>
Khartoum, which banned flights to four locations in Bahr el
Ghazal, has now allowed airdrops in any area within the province
and given WFP permission to use a second C-130 aircraft. Roads
are impassable due to the recent El Nino rains.
</P>
<P>
The move came ahead of the May 2 peace talks with southern
rebels in Nairobi, the second one since 1994.
</P>
<P>
WFP, the food aid arm of the United Nations, has provided
362,237 tons of relief food to an estimated 4.7 million victims
of war and drought in Sudan since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese civil war between the Moslem-ruled government and
rebels in the animist and Christian-dominated south dragged on
into the 14th year in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
