<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Records March Trade in Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- An unexpected surge in imports
pushed South Africa's trade account into the red in March,
dashing hopes of a consecutive monthly surplus, The Star paper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
A deficit of 361 million Rand (72 million U.S. Dollars) was
recorded in March from a surplus of 511 million Rand (101 million
U.S Dollars) in February, the South African Revenue Service was
quoted as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected dip into the red confused economists, who were
expecting a surplus of between 500 million Rand (99 million
Dollars) and 800 million Rand (159 million Dollars) in March.
</P>
<P>
The service said imports jumped 8.5 percent from 10.6 billion
Rand (2.1 billion Dollars) in February to 11.4 billion (2.26
billion Dollars) in March, owing to a 35 percent rise in
machinery imports. Exports remained almost unchanged at 11.1
billion Rand (2.2 billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Economists were expecting imports to slow because of the
sluggish economy. They said the March import figure was "odd"
given the traditional volatility of trade data.
</P>
<P>
Others said the rise in imports could have been prompted by
anticipation of lower interest rates and a weaker Rand.
</P>
<P>
The latest trade data ignited fears that the first-quarter
deficit on the current account might be bigger than the 3.1
billion Rand (615 million Dollars) deficit in the fourth quarter
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Economists warned that the negative impact of the recent
turmoil in east Asia and Zimbabwe, both important export markets
for South African goods, was still to be reflected in export data
in coming months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
