<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Live Water Fowls From Mainland Arrive in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 live ducks and
geese from the Chinese mainland were imported to Hong Kong Friday
morning under new stringent import control measures.
</P>
<P>
These water fowls arrived at two Western Wholesale Food Market
stalls which have been ready to serve as central slaughter and
wholesale outlets for water fowls.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman for the Agriculture and Fisheries
Department, this was the first batch of live water fowls imported
under the new control systems and the policy to segregate chickens
from ducks and geese.
</P>
<P>
"The policy aims to minimize the risk of transmission of avian
influenza H5N1 from water fowls to live chickens and subsequently
to humans," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Those water fowls for export to Hong Kong are segregated from
other birds in mainland farms five days prior to export and tested
negative for the H5 virus, with health certificates signed by a
competent mainland veterinary authority, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The bird flu scare which broke out late last year prompted the
government to slaughter some 1.5 million chickens in Hong Kong in
December and to ban poultry imports from China's mainland in a
bid to curb the spread of the deadly virus.
</P>
<P>
Chicken imports were allowed to resume on February 7 after
strict new hygiene measures were implemented.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
