<HEADLINE> Strong Unions Vital for S. African Future: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- President Nelson Mandela said
Friday strong organization of working people was as important for
the future of South Africa as it was for their own interest.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to mark May Day today in Kimberley, central South
Africa, Mandela said trade union struggles had been part of the
ruling African National Congress' fight for freedom and struggle.
</P>
<P>
South Africa relied on organized workers to strengthen the
offensive against crime and corruption in the work place,
including the criminal justice system and the civil service,
Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
On improvement of living conditions, Mandela said in striving
to improve life of all, people should dispel the idea that change
came from the government alone while people waited passively for
delivery.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that one of the most urgent and critical
challenges facing the country was the creation of more jobs. As
preparations for a job's summit were being finalized, the
government was looking at how it could further enhance job
creation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to relations between trade unions and the
government, Mandela said his government could depend on unions
within the ANC alliance.
</P>
<P>
He said as long as the ANC and its allies -- the Congress of
South African Trade Unions, and the South African Communist Party
-- remained strong and united, it would keep the country on the
path of change.
</P>
<P>
"Above all it will help to ensure that the needs of the
poorest and most vulnerable come first," Mandela said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
