<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-01 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat, Jordanian FM Hold talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
and Jordanian Foreign Minister Jawad Anani held talks in the West
Bank city of Ramallah Friday on the stalled Middle East peace
process, said a senior Palestinian official close to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Arafat briefed Anani on the ongoing
efforts by U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross to break the
deadlock in the Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations, said the
official who declined to give his name.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also mentioned about preparations for next Monday's
London talks which will be separately held by U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
It was widely believed that the London meetings would be
decisive for breaking the deadlock in the Palestinian-Israeli
peace negotiations, which have been stalled for over a year after
Israel broke ground for a settlement project in Arab East
Jerusalem in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ross has held several rounds of talks with Israeli and
Palestinian leaders in an attempt to persuade them to accept a
U.S. proposal on Israel's withdrawal from 13.1 percent of West
Bank before the London meetings.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have pledged to back Washington's suggestion
despite it falls far below their expectation of 40 percent
pullback, but they said they would made no more concessions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel has insisted on rejecting the U.S. plan,
saying that it is only willing to hand over 9 percent of the West
Bank's land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Arafat told the visiting Jordanian minister that so far, there
is no specific policy changes on the Israeli side concerning its
troop redeployment in the West Bank and he is not certain whether
the London talks could make progress in this field.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is scheduled to meet Ross again Friday evening in
Ramallah to hear from him what has been decided by the Israeli
side.
</P>
<P>
And on Sunday, Arafat will fly to Cairo to brief Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on his meetings with Ross and what to be
discussed in the London talks. Egypt is a key Arab mediator in the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Anani, who arrived in Ramallah at noon, has returned home after
his talks with Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
