<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Union Leaders Slap Government's Job Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Germany's trade union leaders jointed
in a chorus Friday to criticize the government's failure to combat
record-high unemployment and call for a policy change in Bonn
after the general elections in September this year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before 5,000 participants in a May Day rally in
Dortmund, leader of the German trade union for public services
OETV Herbert Mai said that Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government was
no longer in a position to win the battle against mass
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the IG Metall metalworkers union Klaus Zwickel also
told a rally in Ingolstadt that Kohl's government had "neither the
ideas nor the power to lead Germany into the 21th century."
</P>
<P>
Job creation and social justice must finally become the focus
of all political activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dieter Schulte, who heads the main trade union federation DGB,
on Friday also voiced sharp criticism over the government policy
of cutting social spending, warning that such a policy would widen
the gaps between the rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
According to DGB estimates, about 500,000 people took part in
the traditional May Day demonstrations and rallies across Germany
Friday to press for more jobs and social justice.
</P>
<P>
With jobless totals hovering at post-war highs of around 4.6
million, unemployment has become a key campaign issue in Germany's
national elections on September 27, in which Kohl is running
against his Social Democratic challenger Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Kohl has been hampered in the battle to cut joblessness after
failing to push through 30 billion German marks (16.5 billion U.S.
dollars) in tax cuts last year. He has also been blamed for
backing down on his promise to halve joblessness by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
