<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lack of Fuel, Power Throws Nigerians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The news of the break-down of one of
Nigeria's two operating refineries Wednesday afternoon might be
the worst news to most people of the country.
</P>
<P>
For sometime this year, most Nigerians have been suffering
from a nightmare resulted from the twin vice-grip of fuel
scarcity and erratic power supply.
</P>
<P>
Lack of petroleum products and electricity has a serious
impact on business which sustains declining capacity utilization,
loss of man-hours, under-productivity, reduced sales, depressed
profit margins, higher cost of production and increased
extra-budgetary expenditures.
</P>
<P>
The losses of the business circle, which is yet to be
prosperous with the uncertainty of the country's political
situation, are estimated at millions of U.S. Dollars a day,
according to the Federal Office of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Apart from small businesses, high-powered institutions such as
the Central Bank of Nigeria and th Nigerian Ports Authority (NPA)
were also caught up by the twin-grip.
</P>
<P>
For a whole week in early March, the Central Bank reportedly
had no power supply because it could not get diesel to power its
generating sets and calculating machines.
</P>
<P>
Interbank checks for transaction among banks estimated at six
million Dollars were stalled that week.
</P>
<P>
The ports under NPA, whose performance is very crucial to a
highly import-dependent country like Nigeria, were paralyzed for
most of March.
</P>
<P>
The same problem: NPA could not power its machines and
equipment for loading and discharging cargoes.
</P>
<P>
For ordinary people, in a local government area of Lagos State
alone, 500,000 inhabitants have lived in darkness for six weeks
running.
</P>
<P>
With the spread of power supply problem across the country,
almost every facet of life is affected, including water supply in
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
In Ogun State, western Nigeria, two kids, aged eight and 10,
drowned in a river in a bid to fetch drinkable water.
</P>
<P>
Erratic power supply is not a new problem in Nigeria due to
aging infrastructure, vandalization of functional facilities and
illegal connections and consumption.
</P>
<P>
Diesel generators of various sizes therefore find a big market
in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the poor situation of refineries has forced most of
the generators out of operation as there is only one of four
refineries now operating far under capacity, resulting in
scarcity of diesel.
</P>
<P>
The supply of gasoline is also in tight shortage, creating
difficulties for people to move around and goods to be
transported to where they are needed.
</P>
<P>
It seems the Nigerian government did not discuss conundrum of
which problem comes first -- power or petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
As a rescue means, the government has ordered the import of
petroleum products for domestic use until the overhaul of the
refineries is completed.
</P>
<P>
Now, turn-around maintenance of the refineries is yet to begin
for some reason despite the funds set aside by the government for
the job.
</P>
<P>
The government has also decided to allocate part of this
year's budget for the rehabilitation of the failing power plants.
But the Ministry of Finance reportedly said it is not in a
position to meet the immediate funding needs.
</P>
<P>
It appears that most Nigerians have to accept the reality
although they are desperately longing for a better life.
</P>
<P>
"When the going gets tough, the tough gets going," said Bola
Adekoya, a sales clerk in a Lagos supermarket. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
