<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Government Hails Ex-Prime Minister's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has hailed
the guilty plea made at the United Nations Arusha Tribunal for
Rwanda (ICTR) by Rwanda's former interim prime minister Jean
Kambanda Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
"It is no surprise that Kambanda has pleaded guilty," Rwandan
Minister of Foreign Affairs, Anastase Gasana told the media.
</P>
<P>
Gasana pointed out that Kambanda, as a ring-leader, was aware
of the enormous amount of evidence, made of videos, recorded
speeches, as well as witnesses' accounts attesting his heavy
involvement in genocide.
</P>
<P>
"It would be very much appreciated if he reveals all he knows
about the genocide plan, its organization, and how it was carried
out throughout the country," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Echoing the view of Gasana, Secretary-General in the Ministry
of Justice Gerard Gahima told foreign reporters that "many people
in Rwanda would welcome it, because here is somebody who was in a
position of leadership and he is willing to tell the truth about
what happened."
</P>
<P>
In a spectacular move Tuesday, the former Rwanda Prime
Minister under the interim government that organized the 1994
genocide, pleaded guilty of all charges leveled against him by
the ICTR.
</P>
<P>
These charges include genocide, conspiracy to commit genocide,
direct and public incitement to commit genocide, as well as
crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda pleaded guilty of all charges and told ICTR President
Judge Laity Kama that no one forced him to do so, and that he was
aware of the consequences of making such a move.
</P>
<P>
"There is really nothing to rejoice about a hard-core criminal
acknowledging the crimes he committed four years after the
genocide was carried out in Rwanda," said Philbert Muzima, the
Secretary-General of "ASRG-Mpore," which is a local association
of genocide survivors.
</P>
<P>
"He should be punished according to the law, and there should
be no lighter sentence for him," Muzima underlined. "Other
criminals roaming throughout the world, or those in jail in
Arusha or in Rwanda should follow suit," he said.
</P>
<P>
The indictment brought in by the ICTR accused Kambanda of
failing in his capacity as interim prime minister to provide
protection to the population.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda's plea occurred only a week after the first 22
genocide suspects tried in Rwanda courts were executed in public.
</P>
<P>
"This sent a strong message to the genocide criminals,"
Minister Gasana said. "The Rwandan government showed that it was
serious about punishing the perpetrators of the genocide," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Because of Kambanda's inflammatory speeches and his repeated
calls to exterminate Tutsis, even regions where residents have
shunned mass-killings of their neighbors like southern Butare
were affected.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda himself ordered the slaughter of Jean Baptiste
Habyarimana who had maintained security in the prefecture of
Butare.
</P>
<P>
More than one million people, mostly Tutsis and some
opposition Hutus were killed during the 1994 genocide that was
conceived and orchestrated by Hutu hard-liners like Kambanda,
Col. Theoneste Bagosora and other dignitaries of late President
Juvenal Habyarimana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
