<HEADLINE> Annan Urges U.S. to Pay U.N. Dues Unconditionally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Friday urged the United States to pay its arrears to the
United Nations without setting any preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Annan was responding to a legislation approved by the U.S.
Senate on April 28 which would provide 819 million dollars in back
U.S. dues to the United Nations. But at the same time, the
legislation sets a precondition to the payment, which imposes a
ban on any U.S. aid to international family planning groups that
lobby for abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his spokesman's office, Annan said he
is pleased to see the level of support in the Senate for payment
of a significant portion of the U.S. arrears to the U.N. system.
</P>
<P>
However, the secretary-general regretted that U.S. fulfillment
of its financial obligation remains uncertain due to an extraneous
matter.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the U.N. system does many things each day which
benefit the citizens of the United States, and of the world.
Conversely, the continuing support of the United States is
critical to the success of the United Nations, he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief urged President Bill Clinton and the
congressional leadership to resolve this issue without any
conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
