<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOFIN Recommends Same 11 Countries for Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The European economy and finance
ministers (ECOFIN) unanimously agreed to recommend the same 11
countries to be the founding members of the single currency, euro.
</P>
<P>
The ECOFIN ministers are to recommend Belgium, Germany, Spain,
France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Austria,
Portugal and Finland for approval to Saturday's summit of European
Union heads of state and government.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by the chairman of the ECOFIN council
meeting, Gordon Brown.
</P>
<P>
The British chancellor of the exchequer also told the press
that following reports by the European Commission, the European
Monetary Institute, the relevant commission recommendation and the
European Parliament opinion, his council adopted the
recommendation on its findings on which member states have
fulfilled the necessary legal as well as economic requirements.
</P>
<P>
"It is not the end of a process but only the beginning of it,"
said the chancellor who added that the single currency will serve
as a platform for stability and growth.
</P>
<P>
The British finance minister said that economic and structural
reforms will be the ensuing challenges on route to fully
materializing the single currency mechanism.
</P>
<P>
The ECOFIN council will recommend the 11 countries to a special
European Parliament session as well as the European Union summit
for final approval.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament, in a Thursday session in Strasbourg,
voted 402-79 with 27 abstentions in favor of the recommendation
made by the European Commission on March 25.
</P>
<P>
The commission recommended the 11 countries to be in the first
wave of euro. Britain and Denmark opted out while Sweden and
Greece were judged not economically ready to join.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the council made any progress in resolving
the row about the candidate for the presidency of the future
European Central Bank (ECB), Brown said that there was some
progress and he believed that progress would continue on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Germany and the Netherlands are backing Dutchman Wim Duisenberg
as the single candidate for ECB presidency whereas France is
championing its central banker Jean-Claude Trichet.
</P>
<P>
Tony Blair, Britain's prime minister, went to the Netherlands
for a lightning visit to talk with his Dutch equivalent Wim Kok on
the candidacy row.
</P>
<P>
European Commission President Jacques Santer said earlier on
Friday that the commission would not breach the Maastricht Treaty
while making the European central banker recommendation.
</P>
<P>
The treaty stipulates that the ECB president serves an
unrenewable eight-year term, though some reports suggested that
the commission was seeking a compromise to let Trichet succeed
Duisenberg in that one eight-year tenure on the grounds of old
age. Duisenberg is now 63 years old.
</P>
<P>
The euro summit has reserved a third day for the choice of the
ECB president, which has been deemed to be the trickiest and
thorniest issue of the summit.
</P>
<P>
Observers here commented that unresolved row would backlash on
the image and stability of euro, to be launched on January 1 next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
