<HEADLINE> Iraq Warns U.N. of Serious Consequences if </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraq warned Friday the U.N. Security
Council of serious consequences if it does not lift its sanctions
on Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Iraq issued the warning in an open letter to the U.N. Security
Council on Friday following a joint meeting of the Revolutionary
Command Council and Iraq's Regional Command of the Baath Socialist
Party.
</P>
<P>
"After eight years and all the sacrifices made by the Iraqi
people, we still cannot see the minimal response from the
Security Council, this will lead to serious consequences," warned
the letter.
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted that the letter is the Iraqi leadership's formal
response to the U.N. Security Council's recent decision to renew
for another six months the sanctions imposed on Iraq in 1990
after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The letter criticized the United States for blocking the
lifting of the trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
In the past eight years, the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM)
on disarmament in Iraq has sent 397 inspection and monitoring
teams to Iraq which involved 3,200 inspectors and arms experts,
said the letter.
</P>
<P>
"Those UNSCOM teams conducted more than 7,000 visits to sites
throughout Iraq, but found no banned weapons of mass
destruction," the letter noted.
</P>
<P>
The non-fly zones created by the United States and Britain in
the north and south of Iraq contradict with the U.N. Charter which
provides non-interference of member states' internal affairs,
the letter said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the United States and Britain maintain military
presence in the Gulf region in order to control the oil fields in
the region and threaten Iraq and other Arab Gulf states.
</P>
</TEXT>
