<HEADLINE> Turkish Demonstrators, Police Clash in Istanbul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Around 5,000 demonstrators clashed
with riot police Friday in Istanbul, the largest city in Turkey,
leaving 74 people injured and 200 demonstrators arrested, local
TV reports said.
</P>
<P>
Chanting anti-government slogans, the demonstrators tried to
force into the Caglayan Square to celebrate the May Day, but were
blocked by heavily armed police.
</P>
<P>
Then the protesters broke into small groups and marched toward
the Taksim Square in downtown Istanbul, where a bloody clash in
May 1, 1977 claimed 30 lives.
</P>
<P>
They clashed with riot police who tried to prevent them from
heading for the square. Angry demonstrators smashed windows of
many roadside shops with sticks and stones and set a truck on
fire.
</P>
<P>
Among the injured were 42 demonstrators, 28 policemen and four
journalists, a police spokesman was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
From the early morning hours, Istanbul police station received
dozens of anonymous phones calls warning that time bombs were
planted in different sites of the city.
</P>
<P>
Police, however, finally found many empty cases and boxes
left in garbage cans. 
</P>
