<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy in Cyprus for Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Presidential Emissary for
Cyprus Richard Holbrooke said here Friday that a settlement to
the protracted Cyprus problem lies in self-efforts by Greek and
Turkish Cypriots more than U.S. mediation.
</P>
<P>
Beginning his second visit to Cyprus within one month,
Holbrooke stressed that Washington cannot make peace or find a
settlement if the parties themselves do not favor it.
</P>
<P>
"Parties must be equally committed to making progress to reach
a viable and lasting solution," he said upon his arrival at the
Larnaca airport.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke's return to Cyprus came at the specific request of
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash. He said he will stay here for three to four days to
hold a series of meetings with the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided into Greek Cypriot-controlled southern part
and Turkish Cypriot-dominated northern part in 1974 when Ankara
landed its troops on the island after a failed coup by Greek
Cypriots seeking union with Greece. The Turkish Cypriot
established a republic in the north, but was only recognized by
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace process came to a standstill last summer when
Denktash walked out of the U.N.-led peace talks with Clerides to
protest a EU decision to open accession talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has said that he will not return to the negotiating
table unless his breakaway republic in northern Cyprus is
recognized and the peace talks are conducted between "two states."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Holbrooke failed in his mission to promote
the resumption of the stalled political dialog between the two
communities.
</P>
<P>
However, he vowed to "try... even if difficulties are very
great."
</P>
<P>
"For a number of reasons we believe we have an opportunity to
move forward now on the substance of issues required to resolve
the Cyprus problem," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
