<HEADLINE> ECB Chief Row Feared to Continue Unresolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Finland dashed on Friday hopes that
it could bring forward a compromise candidate in the row over who
should head the future European Central Bank (ECB).
</P>
<P>
Finnish Finance Minister Sauli Niinisto, upon arriving in
Brussels for a special European economy and finance ministers
council meeting, ruled out the compromise that the Finnish central
banker stands as an alternate candidate.
</P>
<P>
Germany and the Netherlands are backing Dutchman Wim Duisenberg
as the ECB president candidate whereas France is championing Bank
of France governor Jean-Claude Trichet.
</P>
<P>
Duisenberg now heads the European Monetary Institute, the
actual forerunner of the European Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish minister said that the Dutch banker and the French
banker were the only candidates.
</P>
<P>
The row has been feared to ruin Saturday's special summit by
the European Union heads of state and government that, apart from
confirming which member states should be the founding members of
the single currency, is to pick the one candidate to head the ECB
that regulates the euro policy and the exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
Tony Blair, prime minister of Britain that is serving the
rotating presidency of the 15-nation European Union, went to the
Netherlands Friday for a lightning visit to talk with his Dutch
counterpat Wim Kok on the issue.
</P>
<P>
But Kok told Dutch television that he would rather that EU
leaders delayed a decision on who heads the ECB than chose the
wrong man.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands is preparing for its general elections to be
held next Wednesday. The elections are important for Kok and his
labor party as well.
</P>
<P>
European Commission President Jacques Santer brushed aside
earlier on Friday rumors that his commission was seeking a
compromise to arrange for Trichet to succeed Duisenberg on the
ground of age. Duisenberg is now 63 years old.
</P>
<P>
Santer said that the commission would not breach the Maastricht
Treaty that stipulates that the ECB president serves an
unrenewable eight-year term.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Urges Africa to Make Gender Equality a </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the United
Nations Kofi Annan Friday urged African governments, civil
society and the U.N. organizations to make gender equality a
reality.
</P>
<P>
Annan made his call in his concluding remarks at the forum of
heads of state and government at the International Conference on
African Women and Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference closed on Friday by passing
recommendations in four aspects.
</P>
<P>
As for the role of women in developing African economies,
participants recommended, among others, the inclusion of gender
concerns into national budgetary and procedures, the promotion
and protection of women's access to and ownership of land, and
the enhancement of women's access to markets and regional trade.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the participation of women in achieving good
governance, they proposed the launching of a series of trainings
on gender awareness and political skills, the decentralization of
power to enable women to take part in local politics, as well as
the creation of partnerships between women across various
institutions of governance.
</P>
<P>
The participants recommended the establishment of information
centers to enable African women to be beneficiaries of the new
information age.
</P>
<P>
With regards to the issue of creating opportunities for
Africa's new generation, the participants suggested the reduction
of gender imbalances by ensuring equal access to education for
boys and girls, the enforcement of laws that are responsive to
the needs of youths and the provision of proper sexual and
reproductive health information and services to the youth.
</P>
<P>
The participants called upon African heads of state and
governments attending the conference to endorse the outcome of
this conference and use their influence to sensitize other
African heads of state and governments to endorse and implement
the outcome of the conference.
</P>
<P>
They also called upon Secretary-General of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim to take necessary actions
to have the outcome of this conference presented to the
forthcoming summit of African heads of state and government.
</P>
<P>
Some 800 participants from African governments, civil society,
governmental and non-governmental organizations, the U.N.
organizations and agencies as well as international organizations
attended the conference, which was organized to coincide with the
40th anniversary of the founding of the U.N. Economic Commission
for Africa (ECA).
</P>
<P>
Presidents of Botswana and Burkina Faso, prime ministers of
Ethiopia and Algeria, vice-presidents of Ghana and Uganda and ECA
Executive Secretary K.Y. Amoako attended the Friday forum of
heads of state and government.
</P>
<P>
The African leaders who took part in the forum delivered
speeches on the conditions of women in the continent and in their
respective countries.
</P>
<P>
Annan also called on African governments to listen to the
young generation of the continent whom he described as "the
leaders of the 21st century".  
</P>
</TEXT>
