<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's first gold mine, with an annual production
capacity of 200,000 ounces, will begin to be commercially
exploited next June, the Arabic daily World Today reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Geological Survey Authority of Egypt Jaber Naim
said that an Australian company has obtained the right to exploit
the Al-Sukarry gold mine, one of the three gold mines found in the
Eastern Desert.
</P>
<P>
Naim said the mine, with reserves 2 million ounces, had a
mining exploitation maturity of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Profit from the mine, estimated at 600 million U.S. dollars a
year, will be evenly divided by the Egyptian government, the
Australian company and the Geological Survey Authority, he added.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states have taken
measures to control their budget deficits in anticipation of oil
price drop this year.
</P>
<P>
The London-based Arabic newspaper Al-Hayat Saturday quoted
Mohammed Al-Assoumy, Director of the Economic Department of the
United Arab Emirates Industrial Bank as saying that these measures
included abiding by the set expenditure rates while cutting
unnecessary spending in the government departments.
</P>
<P>
The GCC states are Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain, Qatar, the
United Arab Emirates and Oman.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's biggest bank in terms of capital and
deposits, Byblos Bank, has said recently that its net profit in
the first quarter of 1998 rose 125 percent against the same period
last year, to reach 20.5 billion Lebanese pounds (about 13.5
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The total assets of the bank stood at 4,808 billion pounds
(about 3.16 billion dollars) in March, an increase of 17.3 percent
from January.
</P>
<P>
Its customer deposits rose by 14 percent in March against
January to reach 3,440 billion pounds (2.26 billion dollars) while
the customer lending recorded a rise of 9.3 percent in March to
reach 1,410 billion pounds (92.7 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
At the same time, net profit of another Lebanon's leading bank,
Banque Audi, went up 29.1 percent in the first quarter of 1998
compared with that of the same period last year, to reach 10.36
billion Lebanese pounds (about 6.8 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Sources with Banque Audi, which has been expanding its branch
network to increase retail banking, said its cost-to-income ratio
in March 1998 has improved to 58.33 percent from last year's 62.8
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
