<HEADLINE> Turkey Accuses Greece of Supporting Kurdish Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Ministry on Saturday
strongly accused Greece of supporting the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) of Turkey to set up a bureau in Athens.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry statement said that Greece's support and
protection of the PKK group, which is aimed at spoiling Turkey's
territorial integrity, openly violates the act of the United
Nations and international law.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the participation of Acting Greek
Parliamentary Speaker and Greek deputies in the opening ceremony
of the PKK bureau in Athens, capital of Greece, is a
"representation which directly organizes terrorism against
Turkey's territorial integrity".
</P>
<P>
The Kurdish rebel organization PKK has been outlawed for its
struggle to establish an independent Kurdish state in eastern and
southeastern Kurdish areas of Turkey. Nearly 30,000 people,
including policemen, armymen, civilians and the Kurdish rebels
have been killed in the conflicts since 1984 when the rebels
started an armed struggle against the Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz called on
Greece to give up its hostile attitude towards Turkey, warning
that such a stance will impede normalization of the Turkish-Greek
ties.
</P>
<P>
Greece, which is a member state of the European Union
(EU), has been blocking Turkey from entering into the European
organization for its poor human rights record.
</P>
<P>
Greece, however, has categorically denied the charges, saying
that Turkey's claims were aimed at defaming Greece's international
reputation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization, have long been at odds over a number of
issues concerning the Aegean, including air space limits, sea-bed
mineral resources, as well as sovereignty over many uninhabited
islets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0042 </DOCNO>
