<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac to Address Nation on Launching of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 2 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac will
address the nation Sunday on television regarding the launching of
the European single currency euro by the European Union (EU)
summit in Brussels this weekend.
</P>
<P>
In a special program by TF1 television, Chirac will discuss the
event which he considers "historic" and which France has been
working hard to realize since its inception.
</P>
<P>
Chirac is deeply worried about anti-euro agitations at home and
strong opposition to the abandoning of monetary sovereignty by
France to a greater European central bank.
</P>
<P>
In a vote last month on the adoption of the euro at the
National Assembly, the Gaullist Rally for the Republic, a
traditional power base of Chirac's, abstained while the Communist
Party voted against.
</P>
<P>
The extreme-right National Front has called on the French
people to reject "a thousand times" the euro, which it accused of
being a tool to "enslave" France by a Europe engaged in economic
globalization.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, France's mainstream rightwing is in full disarray
after suffering a major setback in the regional elections in March.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference two weeks ago, Chirac called the fear of
euro "groundless and excessive."
</P>
<P>
EU leaders are meeting Saturday in Brussels to give their final
green light to the launching of the euro by January 1, 1999,
despite a lingering dispute over the nomination of the president
of the European central bank.
</P>
<P>
French officials said that a compromise is within reach between
France, which insists on nominating the president of the Bank of
France Jean Trichet, and other EU countries, which prefer Dutch
Wim Duisenberg.
</P>
<P>
In a previous address on March 25, Chirac paid tribute to all
his predecessors, President Valery Giscard d'Estaing and President
Francois Mitterrand, as well as all other French leaders -- both
left and right -- for the contributions to the building of the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
The advent of the euro is a success and the French people look
forward to its future with courage and determination, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
