<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Firms Start Preparations for Transition to Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Greek firms have already started
to prepare for the transition to the euro, the European Union's
common currency, according to a survey released here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Association of Greek Industries
(SEV) in the past two months among 100 local enterprises, shows
that 26 Greek firms have determined the field of application of
their euro plan, 31 have appointed a plan manager, 24 have studied
the consequences from the introduction of the euro, 14 have
defined a transition plan, 11 have already taken concrete action,
and 11 have briefed staff on the plan.
</P>
<P>
The euro is expected to be launched on January 1, 1999, with
the participation of countries such as France, Germany, Italy,
Ireland, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal, Spain, Austria,
Finland and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Greece, Britain, Denmark and Sweden are unlikely to join, but
of the 15 EU members, Greece is the only country which has now not
met the convergence criteria.
</P>
<P>
To join the euro by January 1, 2001, the Greek government has
announced in recent months a series of drastic measures including
the incorporation of its national currency with the European
exchange rate mechanism (ERM) and partial privatization of
loss-making state-run companies and banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
