<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Berger: U.S., China Cooperate on Larger Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. National Security Advisor
Samuel R. Berger said here Friday that the projected U.S.
strategic partnership with China should lead to broader
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In a policy address to the Brookings Institute, he said the
United States has a "great interest" in building a strategic
partnership with China.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's a strategic partnership in the sense that it
should not only be dealing with trade issues and issues that are
of smaller scope, but we should be dealing with the larger issues
where we can cooperate, for example, the future of the Korean
peninsula," Berger said.
</P>
<P>
The United States and China agreed to establish a "constructive
strategic partnership for the 21st century" in October when
Chinese President Jiang Zemin visited Washington and held a summit
meeting with President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral ties have since steadily improved despite some issues
including trade imbalance, human rights, religious freedom,
nonproliferation and particularly the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
"We have, I think, moved the U.S.-China relationship from one
of a downward spiral to at least an upward trajectory," said
Berger, a leading advocate of engagement policy toward China.
</P>
<P>
He added that "what we would like to accomplish is a strategic
partnership in this sense: a relationship in which both sides deal
with each other's strategic interests in a forthright way; where
we find areas of cooperation on which we can work together; where
we deal with our differences candidly, forthrightly and directly,
and what ultimately benefits both our people."
</P>
<P>
Berger made the remarks shortly after U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright left Beijing for Mongolia after two days of
talks with Chinese leaders in preparation for President Clinton's
visit to China in late June.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said his China trip is aimed at building on the
momentum created by the fall Washington summit in the
Sino-U.S. relationship.
</P>
<P>
Berger explained why the United States attaches importance to
China. He said: "How China evolves over the next 10 or 20 years
may be one of the great questions that determines our future.
</P>
<P>
"Whether China is integrated into the global community that I
spoke about, on the one hand, or whether China drifts or heads off
in a more nationalistic, a more insular direction, I think will
determine not only the fate of Asia, but very much our own
future," he added.
</P>
<P>
The official spoke highly of China's policy regarding
nonproliferation and nuclear cooperation with foreign countries.
"The fact of the matter is there are a number of things that they
have not only committed to do, but have done." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
