<HEADLINE> India's BJP Discusses Party Strategies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 2 (Xinhua) -- India's Bharatiya Janata Party
(BJP) decided on Saturday to make fresh efforts to attract
minorities to its fold in a bid to reach out to wider sections and
areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a meeting of the BJP's National
Executive Committee, Gandhinagar, capital of the western state of
Gujarat, according to the Press Trust of India (PTI).
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held ahead of the two-day National Council Session
beginning on Sunday, discussed a draft political resolution to be
approved at the Council session.
</P>
<P>
BJP spokesman Venkaiah Naidu told reporters later that the
party was considering plans to widen its base to reach out to all
areas.
</P>
<P>
In an opening address to the meeting, outgoing BJP president
Lal Krishna Advani expressed confidence that the party would
overcome difficulties faced by the BJP-led coalition government.
</P>
<P>
"The trials and tribulations of the first six weeks of the
Indian government have steeled its resolve to stabilize and
strengthen itself," Advani, also home minister, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda of the three-day National Executive and
Council meetings of the BJP are deliberations on its strategy on
expanding the base of the party and strengthening the
organizational structure. But the most difficult task facing the
BJP leadership is how to project a new image to the party in the
era of coalition politics.
</P>
<P>
The topics of the meetings also include the role of BJP's
allies in the central government and their relations, and ways to
ensure a smooth functioning of the coalition.
</P>
<P>
The newly elected BJP president, Kushabhau Thakre, will
formally take over from Advani at the Council meeting, to be
attended by more than 2,300 delegates from across the country,
including Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, district presidents
and state-level office bearers. 
