<HEADLINE> UK Denies Having Tension with Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The British High Commission in
Harare said here Saturday that relations between Britain and its
former colony, Zimbabwe, are "excellent."
</P>
<P>
The high commission stressed in a statement that workshops are
being held to involve a wide range of local stake-holders in the
process of discussing bilateral aid packages.
</P>
<P>
There was no tension between Britain and Zimbabwe contrary to
some media reports that the Zimbabwean government had not been
invited at a British-organized meeting held here Thursday where
bilateral aid packages and other issues were discussed.
</P>
<P>
"The process of stake-holder consultation is designed to
complement in the formal talks, of which the Zimbabwean
government has a central role," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier media reports said the British government had
deliberately excluded the Zimbabwean government from a review of
priorities for British development assistance to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"The situation has raised serious concern in the Zimbabwean
government, which feels the British government has breached the
code of international relations and basic diplomatic etiquette,"
newspapers published here reported.
</P>
<P>
The papers added that the British side recently had second
thoughts about honoring last year's agreement with the Zimbabwean
government in which they promised a grant aid of more than 200
million Zimbabwean Dollars (over 11 million U.S. Dollars) for the
purchase of 1,500 Land-Rovers for the Zimbabwean police.
</P>
<P>
"This makes it very difficult for the government to have a
smooth working relationship with the British High Commission,"
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Zimbabwean Ministry of Foreign Affairs had
refused to comment on the matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
