<HEADLINE> More Nanjing Massacre Victims' Remains Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Construction workers have found more
remains of victims of the Nanjing Massacre perpetrated by the
Japanese invaders in December 1937.
</P>
<P>
The remains, of four people, had been buried just 15 cm under
the surface of the ground in the courtyard of the Jiangdongmen
Memorial Hall.
</P>
<P>
"We will keep the remains for a future exhibition condemning
Japanese invaders for the atrocities they committed in China,"
said Zhu Chengshan, director of the memorial hall.
</P>
<P>
Historical records bear witness to the fact that Japanese
soldiers killed more than 10,000 Chinese civilians and prisoners
of war at dusk on December 16, 1937, in the area around
Jiangdongmen.
</P>
<P>
A mass grave was found there in 1982, and the local authorities
decided to build a memorial hall on the site in 1983. More than
five million Chinese and overseas people have visited it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
