<HEADLINE> Over 110 Injured in Hong Kong Jet-foil Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 110 passengers and five
crew members were injured when a jet-foil hit an underwater object
near Hong Kong's new airport early Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred about one mile off Tai O at 12:25 p.m.
(local time) when the jet-foil "Flores" carrying eight crew
members and 236 passengers was on its way to Macao, the Government
Information Services (GIS) Department said.
</P>
<P>
Several police launches and Marine department vessels were
dispatched to the scene immediately. All the casualties had been
taken to hospitals for treatment, GIS said.
</P>
<P>
The police have made arrangements for other passengers to
return to town.
</P>
<P>
HKSAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa sent his regards to the
injured. "Staff from all departments concerned and hospitals are
making their best efforts to treat the injured," he said.
</P>
<P>
Director of Home Affairs Shelley Lau went to hospitals to visit
the injured and to ensure that help desks were set up efficiently.
</P>
<P>
"Setting up help desks is one of the recommendations made the
Garley Building Fire investigation report," Lau said. A fire broke
out in the commercial building in November 1996, killing dozens of
people.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time the recommendation has been put into
practice," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Home Affairs Department (HAD) coordinates the running of
the help desks together with staff of the Social Welfare
Department, the Police and the Hospital Authority.
</P>
<P>
HAD will continue in the next few days to offer assistance to
the injured and their families.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Marine Department started an investigation into
the accident.
</P>
<P>
The Marine Department has issued a navigational warning message
to shipmasters and a marine patrol boat will stay at the scene
Saturday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
