<HEADLINE> Operational Headquarters Set Up For Envoy's Rescue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 2 (Xinhua) -- A base of operations to organize the
rescue of the kidnapped Russian presidential envoy to Chechnya was
established Saturday at a meeting of Chechen Republic authorities.
</P>
<P>
Valentin Vlasov was abducted by masked armed men on a road near
the Ingushetian village of Assinovskaya, close to the Chechnya
border early Friday, which makes this the first abduction of a
senior Russian official.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Kazbek Makhashev, who runs Chechnya's
security forces, and other Chechen officials vowed to work closely
together on the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
An investigation directed by Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov
continues, with checkpoints at all main crossroads in the region.
Police say the search has yielded no results so far and the envoy
is still missing.
</P>
<P>
Chechen authorities arrested two suspects Saturday who could be
linked to the abduction. Deputy Chechen Prosecutor General
Magomed Magomadov said Vlasov's bodyguard and driver had been
formally placed under arrest.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chechen Prosecutor General Magomed Magomadov said driver
Sultan Satuyev was "suspected of being connected with the incident
when Vlasov was abducted."
</P>
<P>
The Russian's bodyguard, who was not named, was under
investigation for failing to resist the attack by the kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
The suspects can be held 20 days before charges are brought.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Rybkin, dispatched to the region by Yeltsin on Friday for
urgent talks with senior Chechen officials, said Vlasov's
abduction was intended to further undermine stalemated peace talks
between Moscow and the Chechen capital of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
Chechen and Russia's other North Caucasus republics have become
a fertile ground for hostage-takers since a ceasefire ended the
Chechen war in August 1996, but it has also frozen the question of
Grozny's political status for five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
