<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-European Commercial Ties Keep Positive Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Trade statistics for the first
quarter of 1998 show that China's commercial ties with
Europe have maintained their momentum of growth.
</P>
<P>
The total trade volume in the first three months topped 9.7
billion U.S. dollars, up 11.4 percent from the year-ago period,
according to statistics released by China's General Administration
of Customs.
</P>
<P>
China exported 6.12 billion U.S. dollars-worth of commodities
to Europe in this period, which represented a 30.1 percent
increase, while its imports from the region dropped 10.2 percent
valued at 3.58 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Trade experts here agree that this favorable momentum should be
attributed to the booming commercial activities between the two
sides, the frequent bilateral high-level visits and a deeper
mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
The first quarter's growth was achieved against a background of
progress: Last December the European Commission removed China from
its list of "non-market economies"; on March 25 this year the
European Commission launched a new China policy in a document
titled, "Building a Comprehensive Partnership with China", which
called for more dialogue, wider cooperation and the upgrading of
overall ties with China.
</P>
<P>
The second Asia-Europe Meeting, held in early April, witnessed
China and Europe hold their first summit meeting, at which it was
decided to build a long-term and stable constructive partnership
toward the 21st century, and to establish an annual summit
meeting mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, trade and economic ministers from Portugal, the
Netherlands, Turkey and Germany visited China one after the other
and exchanged views with Chinese officials on bilateral commercial
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The 1990s have also seen the scale of bilateral investment
and financial cooperation enlarged.
</P>
<P>
European Union (EU) countries had invested in 8,352 projects in
China by the end of 1997, involving 31.47 billion U.S. dollars in
contracts, of which 13.05 billion U.S. dollars was actually
used. The EU ranked fifth among the countries and regions
investing in China at that time.
</P>
<P>
China has borrowed most of its foreign government loans from
Europe, whose member countries and official financial
organizations had provided, by the end of last year, contracts
worth 12.808 billion U.S. dollars to China. This accounted for
41.9 percent of such loans China had received.
</P>
<P>
China also introduced, in the same period, 6,864 items of
technology from the EU, with the contracts valued at 38 billion
U.S. dollars, which made up 44.9 percent of China's total
introduction of technologies.
</P>
<P>
However, there are still some problems remaining in bilateral
trade and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
The EU has for a long time accused China of dumping, and
stopped importing some agricultural products from China. It also
discriminates against four kinds of non-textile Chinese products.
</P>
<P>
However, trade experts said, the EU's decision to remove the
"non-market economy" label from China would help solve the
anti-dumping problem. They also noted that the EU would gradually
ease controls on Chinese exports to the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
