<HEADLINE> A Cathay Pacific Plane Lands at HK's New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- A wide-bodied aircraft of Hong
Kong's Cathay Pacific Airways Saturday successfully landed at the
new Hong Kong International Airport at Chek Lap Kok as part of the
first airdrome trial conducted by the Airport Authority.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific's B747-200 aircraft, "the Spirit of Hong Kong
97", landed at Chek Lap Kok at 15:20 and taxied to bay S23 where a
number of ground handling services were performed.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft was then pushed back and was towed to bay S27
where further services were tested, including off-loading of
baggage and cargo, cabin cleaning and technical checks. After a
two-hour trial the aircraft departed from Chek Lap Kok at 17:20
and flew back to Kai Tak. There were no passengers on board the
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's trial was the first time the airdrome facilities and
aircraft ground services had been tested with a wide-bodied
aircraft present.
</P>
<P>
"Today's trial went very smooth and provided a great
opportunity for a number of parties to test airside procedures,"
commented Captain Jeff Turner, Cathay Pacific's General Manager
Operations, Flight Operations Department, who was an observer at
the trail.
</P>
<P>
The airport at Chek Lap Kok is scheduled to be put into
operation on July 6, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
