<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Outbreak Hits Southern Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Apart from the humanitarian
difficulties created by the civil strife in Lower Jubba in south
Somalia, the people of the town of Jilib are now facing a new
outbreak of cholera.
</P>
<P>
More than 10 people are reported to have died of cholera in
Jilib town in the past three days alone.
</P>
<P>
According to Mohamed Abdulle Sandhere, head of Mercy
International, an American aid agency, more than 60 people who
are suffering from cholera are now being isolated in the former
municipal facility of the town.
</P>
<P>
Sandhere said samples taken from the patients for laboratories
in Nairobi have all tested positive cholera. As the people are
being treated with few stocks of anti-cholera drugs, there are
also dozens of others who are falling for the disease as the days
go past.
</P>
<P>
Elders from the town whom this reporter contacted on the VHF
radio said they receive little medical assistance from the few
international aid agencies including Mercy international, United
Nations Children's Fund and the International Committee of the
Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
However, they noted that the assistance is insufficient to
combat the epidemic taken into account its current rate
propagation.
</P>
<P>
The local medical staff have attributed the cholera outbreak
to the recent rains which hit the town and its surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
The medical assistance said the spread of the disease is
supported by poor sanitation and lack of enough latrines for most
of the people in the town, who are internally displaced by last
year's disastrous floods which hit southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The current outbreak of fighting in Lower Jubba is also said
to have added more refugees to the town which is already afloat
with people.
</P>
<P>
The cholera epidemic is one of Somalia's repetitious diseases
that kill hundreds of people each year, especially during the
rainy seasons. More than 200 people, mainly children under five,
are known to have died of the disease in Mogadishu alone early in
the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
