<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Two US-Made Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, May 2 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese Long March 2C rocket
successfully sent two US-made Iridium satellites into orbit from
the Taiyuan Satellite Launch Center in north China's Shanxi
Province late this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The rocket lifted off from the center at 17:16 pm (Beijing
Time).
</P>
<P>
This is the third time that a Long March rocket has carried
into space two Iridium satellites made by the US-based Motorola
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The other two launches were on December 8, 1997 and March 26,
1998, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The continuous overcast and rainy weather with thunder in the
past few days add difficulties to the launch, and every day there
were only 36 seconds for the launch command.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese scientists, however, succeeded in the launch, based
on their rich experience and precise calculations.
</P>
<P>
After 11 minutes, the distributor stage successfully altered
course and boosted the two satellites into their predetermined
orbit at a perigee of 632 km, apogee of 634 km, and bank angle of
86.4 degrees.
</P>
<P>
In line with a contract signed in April, 1993, China in the
coming years will continue to use the Long March 2C rockets to
send 16 Iridium satellites into orbit from the Taiyuan center to
maintain the communications network.
</P>
<P>
Iridium satellites are part of a state-of-the-art mobile
telecommunications system developed by Motorola for Iridium LLC,
which is developing and commercializing a global wireless
communications network that will combine the worldwide reach of 66
low earth orbit satellites with land-based wireless systems.
</P>
<P>
The system offers communications services for individuals,
vehicles, ships and airplanes using handheld telephones, pagers
and other facilities.
</P>
<P>
The 66 satellites are to be launched by Delta 2 rockets of the
McDonnell Douglas Corporation of the United States, Proton rockets
of Russia and Long March 2C rockets of China.
</P>
<P>
The system is expected to go into operation by the end of this
year, when a Delta 2 rocket completes the last launch.
</P>
<P>
Today's launch was the 51st using the Long March rocket series.
</P>
<P>
Since it was put into international commercial service in 1985,
the Long March rockets have sent a total of 15 foreign commercial
satellites into space. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
