<HEADLINE> Taiwan University President Attends Beida Celebrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The president of Beijing University
(Beida), Chen Jiaer, today sat next to Wei Jao Chen, president of
Taiwan University, at a forum for higher education in Beijing to
mark the centennial of Beida.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jao Chen, the first elected president of Taiwan University,
said the most obvious similarity between his university and Beida
is a free and open academic atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Fifty years ago, scholars from Beida took the university's
tradition and influence to Taiwan University, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jiaer said the common cultural tradition and their
respective characteristics have been the basis of exchanges
between the two universities for many years.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, Beida signed a memorandum on mutual cooperation
with its Taiwan counterpart, covering the fields of traditional
Chinese culture, philosophy, psychology, history and economics.
</P>
<P>
Despite some man-made barriers, academic exchange programs,
exchanges of teachers and students' activities such as sports
competitions have also been conducted frequently between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Expressing gratitude for being invited to attend the
celebration of the centennial of Beida, Wei Jao Chen said Beida is
a giant international academic forum.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jao Chen, who will chair the 70th anniversary celebrations
of Taiwan University this year, said exchanges between the two
most prestigious universities on the two sides of the Taiwan
Straits will never be limited to sending congratulations to each
other, adding that he believed that more in-depth exchanges would
be conducted between them in the future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
