<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Presidents of 60 leading foreign
universities and some 20 Chinese universities gathered at the
China World Hotel here today to discuss universities in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The forum is the most important event marking the 100th
founding anniversary of Beijing University (Beida).
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the two-day forum, Chinese
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing described the holding of the forum as the
most glorious event ever in Beida's 100-year history.
</P>
<P>
The university presidents will discuss at the forum the roles
of universities in the 21st century, teaching strategies,
connections between universities and society, and the
administration of universities.
</P>
<P>
Colin Lucas, vice-chancellor of the University of Oxford in
England, said that the grand forum is appealing to every
university administrator with the approach of the new century.
</P>
<P>
Concerning similarities among many universities, he
acknowledged that "it is very important for a university to keep
its unique characteristics."
</P>
<P>
Chang-Lin Tian, professor of engineering and former president
of the University of California, Berkeley, said he believed that
universities in the 21st century must halt the tendency to focus
too much on technology while neglecting the humanities.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jia'er, president of Beijing University, said that both
opportunities and challenges will co-exist in the new century.
</P>
<P>
Wei Zhao Chen, president of Taiwan University, said that
universities across the Taiwan Straits as well as universities in
Hong Kong and Macao should work jointly to probe the combination
of traditional Chinese culture with modern civilization.  
