<HEADLINE> Wreckage of U.S. Bomber On Display in Guangxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The wreckage of a U.S. B-24 Bomber
that crashed during World War II is now on display in the Lingqu
Museum in Xing'an County, in south China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Also on display in the 200-sq-m exhibition hall are relics
discovered in the plane, including parachutes, first-aid
kits, torches, pistols, coins and notebooks as well
as some photographs.
</P>
<P>
Found in October 1996 by two local farmers who were searching
for herbs in the mountains, the bomber has been identified as one
of the "Flying Tigers" squadron led by U.S. Major General Claire
Lee Chennault.
</P>
<P>
It crashed on August 31, 1944 on its way back to Guangxi after
bombing Japanese warships in a Taiwan harbor, killing all the 10
crew members on board.  
</P>
</TEXT>
