<HEADLINE> Pakistani Foreign Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan has resigned from his job, according to a press release
Saturday by the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
It said Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has acceded to a request by
Ayub Khan to reassign his portfolio, enabling him to attend to his
constituents.
</P>
<P>
Ayub Khan has requested the prime minister to "reassign him
portfolio wherein it does not entail leaving the country, enabling
him to be amongst his electorate to work for their well-being and
welfare," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Ayub Khan was appointed as foreign minister on February 25,
1997 after the Pakistan Muslim League (N) won general elections
earlier in the month.
</P>
<P>
During his spell of 14 months as foreign minister, Ayub Khan
had "full support and efforts of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif," and
highlighted the Kashmir issue at all international fora, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
It also said Ayub Khan has had the Foreign Service Reforms
approved, started talks with India and initiated talks between the
Afghan Taliban militia and the rival Northern Alliance in
Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Foreign Ministry said Saturday that Siddique
Khan Kanju, the state minister for foreign affairs, has been asked
to look after the Foreign Ministry before a new foreign minister
is appointed.  
</P>
