<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Begins Shuttle Diplomacy in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
Saturday insisted on the demand for international recognition of
his regime in northern Cyprus as U.S. presidential envoy Richard
Holbrooke began a shuttle diplomacy to revive the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before meeting with Holbrooke in Turkish
Cypriot-controlled northern part of Nicosia, Denktash said a
statement made by the U.S. envoy on Friday is "irrelevant."
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke told reporters upon his arrival here Friday night
that neither the U.S., nor the U.N. and the European Union (EU)
can recognize the Denktash's breakaway state, unilaterally
declared in 1983 and recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Holbrooke has to say things diplomatically but we are not
going to change our position," Denktash said.
</P>
<P>
"We exist and we are going to exist as Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus," he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that "if you want Cyprus to be united, two states are
ready to unite. If not, Cyprus be divided."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek Cypriot-controlled south
and Turkish Cypriot-dominated north in 1974 after Turkey landed
troops on the island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union
with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace process came to a standstill last summer when
Denktash walked out of the U.N.-led peace talks to protest a
European Union decision to open accession talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has said that he will not return to the negotiating
table, unless the peace talks are conducted between "two states,"
instead of two communities.
</P>
<P>
After his 90-minute meeting with Denktash, Holbrooke came to
the Greek Cypriot side of Nicosia to have a working lunch with
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides. He is expected to meet
Denktash again after discussions with Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believed that Holbrooke has brought here a
formula for talks with the two Cypriot community leaders in an
effort to break the current deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
