<HEADLINE> President Clinton Visits Silicon Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said
that "computer technology has revolutionized every aspect of
American industry" during a visit to Silicon Valley on Friday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks not in a computer company, but in Therma Inc.,
a maker of air conditioning and heating equipment.
</P>
<P>
The president told sheet metal workers that their firm has
proved that "Silicon Valley's economic revolution does not just
include computer programming." The firm's biggest customers are in
the computer industry and biotech companies.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has been on a four-day visit to California devoted
mostly to raising two million U.S. dollars at three political
fund-raisers and spending time with daughter Chelsea, a freshman
at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
While speaking in Therma Inc., he urged Congress to approve the 18
billion dollars to replenish the International Monetary Fund. He told
the workers that U.S. exports played a significant role in America's
economy, and that they could sag if foreign economies experience a
downturn.
</P>
<P>
Thirty percent of U.S. exports go to Asia, he said. "(The Asian
countries) are an important part of our future," he said, "And I
think we ought to pay our fair share to the IMF."
</P>
<P>
California, America's first trillion-dollar economy, has strong
economic and trade ties with Asia and is likely to suffer more than
the rest of the country from a slowdown in sales to Asia and visits
from Asian tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
