<HEADLINE> Poland Welcomes U.S. Senate's Approval of NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Aleksande
Kwasniewski on Friday welcomed the U.S. Senate's approval of the
expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
In a letter addressed to U.S. President Bill Clinton,
Kwasniewski also thanked Clinton for his supports in Poland's bid
for NATO membership, the Polish Press Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
After a fierce debate, the U.S. Senate on Thursday voted 80-19
to approve funding for NATO's eastward expansion, with Hungary,
Poland and the Czech Republic as first group of its new members.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, Polish Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek said the
U.S. senate's approval of NATO expansion means that there is only
one step left for Poland to join the Western military bloc.
</P>
<P>
Poland's NATO membership, he said, will help its bargaining
into the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The Polish entry into NATO is not directed against Russia, its
former ally in the now defunct Warsaw pact group, the prime
minister stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
