<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 68 Kurdish Rebels Killed in Military Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish government troops have
killed 68 rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in
the current military operations in eastern and southeastern
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported on Saturday
that with the support of the Turkish warplanes and Cobra
helicopters, about 40,000 Turkish government troops took part in
the military operations codenamed "Murat" in the provinces of
Diyarbakir, Bingol and Mus starting from April 25.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Turkish security forces killed five
of a group of PKK militants at Cudi mountain and Deytussebap town
of Sirnak province, who infiltrated into the Turkey from northern
Iraq, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, there are around 4,800 PKK
guerrillas involved in the separatist war, 2,300 in eastern and
southeastern Turkey and 2,500 in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels, who have sheltered in northern Iraq, often
cross into Turkey to attack Turkish military and civilian targets
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 14-year-old bloody war against the
Turkish government in an attempt to establish an independent
"Republic of Kurdistan" in eastern and southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
More than 35,000 people, including PKK rebels, government
soldiers and civilians have been killed in armed conflicts since
August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
