<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former S. African Generals to Face TRC Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing chief of the South
African National Defense Force Georg Meiring and retired army
general Kat Liebenberg will face hearing of the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC).
</P>
<P>
The two apartheid-era military generals will be questioned on
Monday at a closed-door session in Cape Town on a 1993 raid in
which five sleeping children were killed, said sources from TRC,
a special court authorized by the government led by President
Nelson Mandela, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The raid was carried out by the then apartheid military on a
house in Umtata, Eastern Cape, which was wrongly believed to be a
base of the Azanian People's Liberation Army (APLA), an
anti-apartheid guerrilla group.
</P>
<P>
Meiring and Liebenberg will be questioned on all operational
orders and instructions to the 12-member team which carried out
the raid on October 8 1993, TRC official Dumisa Ntsebeza said.
</P>
<P>
The TRC also wants the two generals to name the people
involved in the planning of the operation and to provide details
of intelligence reports that led to the operation.
</P>
<P>
Ntsebeza said that a police sergeant, Thapelo Mbelo, gave
testimony on the Umtata raid to a closed TRC inquiry last month.
Mbelo was involved in intensive police investigations into APLA
activities at that time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Building Industry Grows by 4.2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The Building Industries
Federation South Africa (Bifsa) has reported a 4.2 percent growth
rate in real terms for the building industry during 1997.
</P>
<P>
Figures recently released from the South African Reserve Bank
revealed that the total turnover reached 21.5 billion Rand (4.3
billion U.S. Dollars) in nominal terms, 11.9 percent up than in
1996, Saturday Star newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Ian Robinson, executive director of Bifsa, said in a statement
that the residential sector had shown no real growth in the
10-billion-Rand (two-billion-Dollar) turnover, whereas the
non-residential sector rose by eight percent in real terms, with
a total turnover of just over 11 billion Rand (2.2 billion
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
But the paper did not say when the statement was made.
</P>
<P>
There was a gradual decline during the four quarters of 1997,
with growth in the third and fourth quarters stabilizing. A much
lower growth rate is evident when compared to the same periods in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The construction industry has since 1980 accounted for almost
half the total gross domestic fixed investment. However, since
the middle of 1991, and particularly during the past six years,
there has been a steady decline to where it now stands at 35
percent of the total fixed investment in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The main reason for this change has been a result of
significant advances in information technology in the machinery
and equipment sector from just above 30 percent to 50 percent in
17 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
