<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Rights Group Urges Laws Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The South Africa Human Rights
Commission (SAHRC) has expressed concern about pornography on the
Internet, saying it will ask parliament to make stricter laws to
curb the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
SAHRC spokesperson Anne Routier said at the weekend that
pornography on the Internet had arisen because it appeared that
neither current nor coming legislation dealt expressly with
distribution of pornographic material through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The commission was extremely concerned about the abuse and
violation of children for pornographic purposes and condemned the
use of the Internet for such purposes.
</P>
<P>
Given the increased use of the Internet as both communications
and entertainment channel, and also the relatively easy access to
the net for both children and adults, this aspect of the law
requires urgent attention," Routier said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the opposition National Party in the country also
made complaints about child pornography circulated on the
Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
