<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers in Hebei Province Favor Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Wang Junhuai, a farmer in north
China's Hebei Province, presses a few keys on his new personal
computer and finds answers appearing on the screen. That is how
Wang manages his small business.
</P>
<P>
Wang, a good hand at computer technology, is a farmer living in
the Liuxinzhuang Village in the suburbs of Shijiazhuang City,
capital of Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
"I save a lot of time in managing my own business with this PC
586, and don't need thick account books any more. I turn on the
computer, and everything is clear," Wang said proudly.
</P>
<P>
He said that about 31 other families in his village have bought
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
But Wang Libin, another villager, had to persuade his parents
to buy a computer with money set aside for indoor decoration.
</P>
<P>
"I hope to learn more skills and techniques; that is why I
bought this computer," he said. With this computer, Wang, who
works in a village-run factory, helped his factory solve many
problems.
</P>
<P>
However, his colleague, Wang Su'e, bought a computer for her
child in 1996. She hopes the computer will be able to help her
child improve his studies with a set of educational software.
</P>
<P>
"It is worth the money only if the computer is helpful to my
child's study," she said.
</P>
<P>
The young men in the village interested in computers have
formed a society to learn the technology, said Wang Xueping,
deputy secretary of the village's committee of the Chinese
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
The village has also decided to take out some money to allow
their computers to be connected with the Internet. The village
last year reported a net income of 260 million yuan, with the
annual income per capita reaching 5,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
More and more personal computers will enter the well-to-do
farmers' families with rapid development in the rural economy,
said Shi Yuzhen, an official in charge of the administration of
computers in the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Hebei Province bought nearly 100,000 PCs last year,
which created a big potential market for computer manufacturers,
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
