<HEADLINE> 18 Zambian Political Leaders Buy Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen political leaders have
bought parastatal companies in Zambia since the country started
its privatization program in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Saturday quoted the Chief Executive of the
Zambia Privatization Agency (Zpa), Valentine Chitalu, as saying
here Friday that the politicians were subjected to the normal
process of bidding in which some of them were not successful.
</P>
<P>
Among those named as successful bidders are former central
committee member of the now opposition United National
Independence Party (UNIP), Yorum Mumba, who was sold Eagle Travel
which was also competed for by the National Chairman of the
ruling Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD), Sikota Wina and
his wife in 1992, according to Chitalu.
</P>
<P>
Hartley farms was sold to Deputy Land Minister Gilbert Mululu
who competed with now Commerce, Trade and Industry Minister Enock
Kavindele.
</P>
<P>
Lima Party Publicity Secretary Stanford Hlazo was sold the La
Hacienda Hotel of Mumbwa but it was not indicated whom he
competed with in the bid.
</P>
<P>
Former Finance Minister Ronald Penza bought Nchanga farms of
Mbala while his wife Jane bought the Zambia Consolidated Tyre
Services.
</P>
<P>
Other winners named are Works and Supply Minister Duresh
Desai, Deputy Community Development Minister Steph Mnjata, former
Land Minister Chulu Kalima and Deputy Labor and Social Security
Minister Syacheye Madyenkulu.
</P>
<P>
Among those named as unsuccessful bidders are Kavindele
who failed to win any tender out of the four he had put in
on various companies.
</P>
<P>
Other unsuccessful applicants include Vice-President Christon
Tembo and Energy and Water Development Minister Ben Mwila who
sought to buy Chilongo farms and Rop respectively.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 326 parastatal companies in the country 213 have
now been put in private hands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
