<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diplomatic Furor Looming Between Zimbabwe, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 2 (Xinhua) -- A diplomatic furor is looming
between Zimbabwe and Britain following the latter's organization
of a private meeting with 14 selected Zimbabweans to discuss a
new strategy for future British aid to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Normally, bilateral aid packages are discussed at
government-to-government level. But none of the 14 invitees to
the Thursday meeting which was organized by the British
Department for International Development in Harare directly
represent the government, The Herald daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The situation has raised serious concern in the Zimbabwean
government, which feels the British government has breached the
code of international relations and basic diplomatic etiquette,
diplomatic sources said.
</P>
<P>
"By circumventing the government, the British are indirectly
sending a very strong message that they have lost confidence in
the capacity of the present government to interpret its needs and
therefore those of its people," one source said, adding that it
would be justifiable for the government to think that relations
were no longer state to state.
</P>
<P>
"This makes it very difficult for the government to have a
smooth working relationship with the British High Commission,"
another source said.
</P>
<P>
Recently the British were reported to have had second thoughts
about honoring last year's agreement with the Zimbabwean
government in which they promised a grant aid of more than 200
million Zimbabwean Dollars (over 11 million U.S. Dollars) for the
purchase of 1,500 land rovers for the Zimbabwe republic police.
</P>
<P>
After their own assessment, the British side has predicted
political instability in Zimbabwe, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to a letter to the invitees, most of whom with no
known constituencies, the workshop would be the first in a series
planned to obtain views of Zimbabweans on the "issues and
priorities" for British aid over the next few years. The process
of defining the new aid strategy to Zimbabwe is scheduled to be
completed by September.
</P>
<P>
"We will be revising our aid to Zimbabwe. The new strategy
will be prepared on the basis of extensive consultations in
Zimbabwe, both with the government and non-governmental
representatives," read the letter.
</P>
<P>
However, the Zimbabwean Ministry of Foreign Affairs has
refused to comment on the matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
