<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Increases Minimum Wages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has raised
the general minimum wages in industrial and agricultural sectors
by 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Labor Day celebrations here Friday, Labor
Minister Joseph Ngutu said the hike would help cushion workers'
purchasing power against inflation, local press reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
But workers in the country demanded the amendment of the
current wage guidelines to give their respective unions the
leeway to negotiate for up to 100 percent compensation for lost
purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
Ngutu told workers at the rally that the government was
examining the possibility of discarding current practice which
pegs salary increases to the cost of living and attaching it to
productivity and the forces of supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
The government is in the process of establishing a
productivity enhancement and measurement center to research and
advise on how to raise productivity in the labor market, he
added.
</P>
<P>
On child labor, the minister said a Children Bill would be
introduced in Parliament to strengthen the legislative protection
of children in the country.
</P>
<P>
He announced that a National Council of Children Services
would be set up to supervise, control and coordinate all child
welfare activities and advise the government on aspects of the
welfare of children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
