<HEADLINE> Private Sector of Economy Growing in Southwest Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The private sector in southwest
China's Sichuan Province has achieved rapid progress thanks to the
local government's preferential policies to encourage private
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that the number of self-employed people increased
by six percent in 1997 and privately owned businesses increased 23
percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the province's self-employed workers gained
5.3 billion yuan in industrial value, up 30.5 percent over
1996. And the sales turnover of the sector reached 34.4 billion
yuan, increasing by 37.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Privately owned enterprises generated 15.6 billion yuan of
industrial value, up 20 percent, and 8.4 billion yuan of sales
turnover, an increase of 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
Provincial officials said the local government has given the
private sector a bigger role in economic growth. The provincial
government has put no limits on the sector's development speed,
scale, managerial system or form of operations.
</P>
<P>
The self-employed and privately owned businesses that do well
have been permitted to adopt share-holding reforms. Since 1997, 36
privately owned enterprises have annexed or purchased more than
270 state-owned and collectively owned firms.
</P>
<P>
So far, 2,000 privately owned enterprises each have at least
one million yuan in industrial value or sales income, including 14
with 100 million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Training Managers of State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province has launched an extensive training program to teach
management skills in business administration, marketing and sales
to state-owned enterprise managers.
</P>
<P>
The goal is to train managers of local state-owned enterprises
and their replacements, who will be able to help the state economy
take off within the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning, which has nearly 10 percent of the country's medium-
and large-sized state-owned enterprises, is China's oldest
industrial production center. Many local state-owned enterprises
are suffering losses.
</P>
<P>
A shortage of qualified managers is one of the factors in the
losses, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
They said that Liaoning will have 1,000 enterprise management
personnel study for master's degrees in business administration,
train 2,000 licensed accountants, and develop a 10,000-member
sales and marketing team.
</P>
<P>
Managers of 1,000 local medium- and large-size state-owned
enterprises and 10,000 managers of non-state sector firms will
receive at least a three-month training program of business
administration before the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 managers of state-owned enterprises have finished
their training courses and returned to their jobs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
