<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills 26 in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-six Zimbabweans have died of
cholera since February this year, while 744 others are suspected
of having been infected with the disease, The Herald daily
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the cases were reported in Manicaland and Masvingo
provinces in south Zimbabwe while five cases were in the capital
Harare.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Ministry of Health and Child Welfare has
discouraged large gatherings in areas without adequate safe water
and sanitary facilities to curb the spread of cholera.
</P>
<P>
"All organizations wishing to hold large gatherings, including
funerals in the affected areas, should apply for clearance from
their provincial medical directorate," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Cholera is caused by drinking contaminated water and eating
dirty food. The Ministry of Health and Child Welfare has since
launched a campaign to discourage people from eating cold and raw
food.
</P>
<P>
The campaign by the ministry also encourages people to use
public toilets and to increase their quantities of fluids if they
suspect having cholera. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
