<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Fair to Help Open Up Central, Western China to Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- A trade fair on economic and
technical cooperation scheduled for October is designed to
introduce China's central and western regions to the world, said
Li Haifeng, vice-director of the Office of Overseas Chinese
Affairs of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the fair sponsored by the office and the Hunan
provincial government October 17-20, Li said the event signals the
central government's support for economic development and the
opening-up of the central and western regions.
</P>
<P>
"The competition in economic and technological fields and the
overall national strength in international markets is becoming
more fierce, especially after the Southeast Asia financial
crisis. This has made China's efforts to attract overseas
investment more difficult," Li said.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the trade fair, to be held in Changsha, Hunan's
provincial capital, can be approved by the State Council
illustrates China's resolve to develop the economy in a sustained
manner and to continue to vigorously attract overseas investment."
</P>
<P>
Li is upbeat about China's prospects for attracting overseas
investment, pointing to China's stable political situation and
sound economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
She said the projected trade fair is designed to promote the
participation of foreign businesses and overseas Chinese, as well
as investors from Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, a similar fair in 1996 in Zhengzhou was a
great success, drawing over 6.9 billion US dollars of investment
to central and western regions by investors from more than 30
countries and regions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
