<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zambia Suffers Forex Shortage and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Rong Shoujun)
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is suffering a critical
shortage of foreign exchange and the currency Kwacha has been
depreciating drastically.
</P>
<P>
This will hinder the country in its effort to realize its
targeted 5.5 percent gross domestic product (GDP) growth.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian Kwacha continues depreciating in the past four
months, falling steadily in value from 1,330 last December to an
average of 1,950 per U.S. Dollar late this week at most of the
commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zambia's foreign reserves have declined to the
lowest level in the past eleven months, and could only meet about
seven weeks of national import requirements in case of a
disaster, according to the latest weekly newspaper Financial
Times.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's reserves, which reached 255 million U.S. Dollars last
September and dropped to 237 million U.S. Dollars three months
later, fell further to 165 million U.S. Dollars in February this
year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the country's gross domestic product can only
grow by about 3.5 percent instead of the estimated 5.5 percent,
an earlier economic report released by the Barclays Bank (Zambia)
said.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of foreign exchange and constant depreciation of
the Kwacha can be attributed to the country's huge debt
servicing, lack of balance of payment support, unexpected
importation of food as well as the failure of the privatized
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), the country's biggest
foreign exchange earner and supplier.
</P>
<P>
Zambia spent 208 million U.S. Dollars last year and another 40
million U.S. Dollars between January and April this year to serve
its foreign debt which now stands at 7.1 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country has also not been receiving balance of payment
support since the foiled military coup last October and the
subsequent detention of opposition leaders, which has drastically
tarnished Lusaka's international image.
</P>
<P>
And the Zambian government has imported 250,000 tons of maize
and mealie meal worth of 40 million U.S. Dollars since last
October to deal with the food shortage due to bad harvest in the
1997/1998 season.
</P>
<P>
Finally, ZCCM's failure to constantly supply foreign exchange
also worsens the situation. ZCCM had not released any funds
until last week when it supplied 20 million U.S. Dollars which is
not enough for the market.
</P>
<P>
However, ZCCM can not be blamed because the conglomerate
itself now faces great operational difficulties and the copper
price has remained low on the world market.
</P>
<P>
To straighten out the situation, the Bank of Zambia (BOZ) is
determined to take measures, Jacob Mwanza, governor of the
central bank, revealed to journalists at a news conference held
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The governor announced that BOZ will siphon the excess Kwacha
from circulation to lessen the demand on foreign currency in
order to curb the continous depreciation of the Kwacha and
stabilize the country's foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, local reports quoted a senior BOZ official
as saying that the central bank is inclined to take control
measures on foreign exchange, but the reports were denied later
by the bank.
</P>
<P>
Whether the central bank of Zambia can effectively deal with
the present situation without huge inflows of foreign currency,
and whether the reduction of Kwacha's supply can help eventually
and fundamentally to diversify the high demand of foreign
exchange, remain to be seen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
