<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chittagong, Haven for Drug Trafficking: Magazine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's largest port city
Chittagong has turned into one of the outposts on the world's
busiest route for drugs and narcotics trafficking, the latest
issue of Observer Magazine available here reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 700 kilograms of narcotics are being illegally
exported out of Bangladesh through the port every year, the
magazine quoted the Department of Narcotics Control (DNC) as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Chittagong port had shot up in importance as clearing center of
drugs and narcotics in Southeast Asia, it said.
</P>
<P>
Narcotics wrapped in paper make their passage into Chittagong
mainly from poppy growing fields of northern Myanmar which is
called South Asian's "Golden Triangle", the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar drugs get passed to the port through the Chittagong
Hill Tracts, it said, adding a considerable quantity of drugs and
narcotics also reaches Chittagong route from Afghanistan, Pakistan
and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of narcotics and drugs that pour into Chittagong
through traffickers finally get dispatched by sea onto the West
and America, and the crew of ships usually act as drug carriers
from Chittagong port.
</P>
<P>
The DNC in Chittagong seized 30 kilograms of narcotics over
past three years and over 50 persons were rounded up on charge of
drugs trafficking in the period, and the sea customs also
separately hauled a considerable quantity of drugs in the past,
the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
At present, Bangladesh's customs authorities and the DNC appear
unable to deal with the staggering drug traffickers mainly for
lack of expertise knowledge on narcotics, effective intelligence
network and transports.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi officials concerned have called for introducing
specialized training for staff to deal with this increasing menace
of drug trafficking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
