<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Expatriate Workers Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The total number of new expatriate
workers from January to March this year was 35,125 in comparison
to 31,982 for the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
Of this figure, nearly 25,000 persons had been recruited by
agencies approved by the Sri Lankan Bureau of Foreign Employment
(SLBFE) while the balance had found jobs on their own, probably
through friends and relatives, SLBFE sources said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka received 65 billion rupees (1.08 billion U.S.
dollars) in foreign exchange by way of remittances from expatriate
workers in 1997 compared to 46 billion rupees (770 million
dollars) in 1996, an increase of over 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The SLBFE is set up to provide 200,000 new jobs abroad in this
year. In this context, the SLBFE has already taken initiatives to
find new job markets in countries such as Malaysia and Singapore,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are about one million Sri Lankan workers
overseas, of whom 600,000-700,000 are in the Middle East and more
than 70 percent are reportedly females. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
