<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Industrial Output Value Up 12.8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's industrial output value
reached 47,267 billion Vietnamese dong (3.6 billion U.S. dollars)
in the first four months of this year, a year-on-year 12.8 percent
increase, the Vietnam News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's state-owned sector had a growth rate of 10.8 percent,
the non-state sector, 6.1 percent, and the foreign invested
sector, 21.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth rates of these three sectors were lower
than those of the previous period. The growth rate of state owned
sector fell by 0.8 percent, the foreign invested sector by 0.3
percent, and the non-state sector by 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The output value increased 11.5 percent in Ho Chi Minh City and
8.5 percent in Hanoi as compared with 13.5 percent and 12.7
percent, respectively, of the previous period.
</P>
<P>
But key industries maintained high growth rates, with the
cement industry up 30.7 percent, crude oil up 20.8 percent, power
up 15.5 percent and garment and textiles up 8 to 9.8
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
