<HEADLINE> Private Firms Report Foreign Debts to Bank Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- As many as 1,800 private companies
in Indonesia have reported their foreign debts worth between 63
billion and 64 billion U.S. dollars to Bank Indonesia, the central
bank, an official said.
</P>
<P>
The number of private companies reporting their debts has
increased after the government obliged every private firm which
has foreign debts to report to Bank Indonesia, Chairman of the
Team for Private Corporate Debts Radius, said here Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Of Indonesia's offshore debts amounting to 133.687 billion U.S.
dollars by April 1998, 67.686 billion dollars were corporate
debts.
</P>
<P>
"Banks' debts should also be addressed as they could hamper
economic activities and bank facilities. Therefore, we still need
much time to settle the trade financing affairs," Radius said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian debtors are scheduled to meet with their foreign
creditors in Tokyo on May 8-10 to discuss the settlement of the
country's external corporate debts, officials said.
</P>
<P>
"We begin to talk about a strategy we are going to use in
settling the corporate debts, including bank debts," he added.
</P>
<P>
The huge amount of corporate debts is one of the reasons of the
depreciation of the Indonesian currency rupiah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
