<HEADLINE> Shenyang Seeks to Attract Massive Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investment will continue
to increase in Shenyang, capital of northeast China's Liaoning
Province, even though Asian investors might reduce investments in
the city because of the Southeast Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The city expects to attract one billion US dollars of overseas
investment this year, with 400 more foreign-funded enterprises put
into operation.
</P>
<P>
The city approved 742 foreign-funded projects last year, and
overseas cash flow into the city reached 868 million US dollars
in 1997, up 40 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
About 50 percent of the new contractual overseas investment
will come this year, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Shenyang will turn to Europe, North
America and Australia to seek potential investors. Meanwhile, it
will cooperate extensively with well-known multinational companies.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang plans to select 172 medium- and large-sized
state-owned enterprises, and eight-to-10 private businesses for
cooperation with overseas investors, and support them to explore
international markets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
