<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian President Praises Government's Euro Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro
Friday praised the work of the center-left government and the
goverment's opposition which helped Italy enter the European
single currency.
</P>
<P>
At a May Day ceremony in the presidential Quirinal Palace,
Scalfaro said the road towards the single currency began with
"tragic conditions" in 1992 when bouts of currency speculation
drove the Italian lira out of the European exchange rate mechanism
and into devaluation.
</P>
<P>
It would be unimaginable for Italy to enter the euro system as
a founding member without the positive and efficient work of the
government, the president said.
</P>
<P>
He warned, however, that the government still had many
difficulties, such as high unemployment and the national debt, to
deal with after its entry into the euro system.
</P>
<P>
Of Italy's public debt, which is still of special concern to
Germany and the Netherlands, Scalfaro said: "We know this and have
never denied it."
</P>
<P>
Italy has a debt-to-gross domestic product (GDP) ratio of 121.6
percent, much higher than the EU's suggested ratio of less than 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
The president said he was moved by the historic occasion of the
euro's arrival and reaffirmed that the single currency was only
the first step towards a Europe of the European people, "people
who can finally unite and say no to war in a century which has
seen so many tears and so much blood".
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament approved Thursday the European
Commission's recommendation for 11 countries to join the single
currency mechanism in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, recommended that Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Ireland,
Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and Finland
be the founding countries of the single currency, the
euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
