<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalian Upgrades Water Supply Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Dalian, a major port city in
northeast China's Liaoning Province, has significantly improved
urban water supply networks and facilities in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The city achieved a daily water supply capacity of 1.2 million
cu.m. following the 1997 completion of the third phase of a
project to divert water from a local river. Nonetheless, the water
supply capacity in urban areas has remained inefficient due to
ageing water supply pipelines and pressurized water pumping
stations.
</P>
<P>
The new upgrading project will be carried out at a total
investment of 1.19 billion yuan, including a Japanese loan
totalling 5.5 billion Japanese yen, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
The project will include the construction of a water pumping
plant with a daily production capacity of 300,000 cu.m, a water
purification plant capable with a daily capacity of 400,000 cubic
meters and the installation of a 89.1-km water supply pipeline
with a diameter of 1.82 meters, as well as the introduction of new
treatment processes to the city's two existing water supply
pipelines. The project will be completed over a five year period.
</P>
<P>
Completion of the project will provide Dalian with annual
savings of 22.7 million yuan on power bills. The savings will
accrue from changing outdated multiple pressure water supplies to
a single pressure system. In addition, the city's daily water
supply capacity will rise from 1.2 million cu.m. to 1.31 million
cubic meters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
