<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Refugees Enter Thailand to Flee Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Some 25,000 Cambodians, mostly Khmer
Rouge dependents, crossed into the northeastern areas of Thailand
Friday when Cambodian government forces launched an attack at the
base of the guerrillas at Anlong Veng.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's Bangkok Post quoted Thai military sources as saying
that Anlong Veng, the headquarters of the Khmer Rouge guerrillas
led by Ta Mok, was completely controlled by government forces at
about noon time Friday.
</P>
<P>
As the Cambodian government forces pushing for Anlong Veng,
thousands of Khmer Rouge dependents began to gather near Sangam
Pass on the Thai-Cambodian border late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thai troops manning a gate at Sangam Pass allowed the Cambodian
civilians to enter Friday.
</P>
<P>
The refugees, estimated at about 25,000, were later moved to a
site and would be allowed temporary stay, probably only a few days
before they are sent back across the border to the care of the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), Thai
military sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian government has contacted the Thai military,
saying they had asked the UNHCR to take care of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
Thai military sources said a camp would be set up on the
Cambodian soil to accommodate the refugees.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian government also assured Thai military that the
Khmer Rouge dependents would be safe once they are back and they
will also be allowed to participate in the July 26 election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
