<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Machine for Cutting Metal Saves Energy, More Efficient </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua)-- A Chinese scientist has developed a
petrol-driven metal dicing machine that can replace the widely
used oxyacetylene metal-cutting machine.
</P>
<P>
Experts here believe the patented petrol-driven machine is the
world's most advanced for metal dicing in terms of energy-saving.
</P>
<P>
The development of the machine had been a state major research
program in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
If 200,000 petrol-driven cutting machines were used in Chinese
factories, 20 billion yuan (2.4 billion US dollars) would be saved
each year, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The machine, developed by Zhong Gonglue, 38-year-old board
chairman of the Beijing Gonglue Zhonggong Petrol-Driven Dicing
Technology Company, can also make the metal dicing process safer.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the metal utilization ratio will be improved
from 65 percent to 85 percent because of the more accurate
character of the machine.
</P>
<P>
The petrol-driven dicing process also reduceds pollution.
</P>
<P>
Acetylene has been the main source of thermal cutting for a
long time. It not only causes environmental pollution but also
consumes more energy.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based company has signed contracts with a venture
in Beijing and others in four provinces to jointly produce the
machine.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
