<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Massive Cuban Parade Lashes U.S. Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds-of-thousands of Cubans
paraded on Friday in celebration of International Workers' Day,
vowing support for socialism and protesting the embargo by the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Paraders waved national flags and banners with slogans backing
socialism and condemning the U.S. embargo as they marched in the
main parade in Havana's Revolution Square. The parade was reviewed
by President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the parade, Pedro Ross Leal, general secretary
of the official trade union, Central de Trabajadores de Cuba
(CTC), gave a speech demanding the total and unconditional end to
the 36-year U.S. economic sanctions against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"The only ethical thing to do is to totally and unconditionally
lift the blockade," he said.
</P>
<P>
The CTC leader said Cuban workers were determined to continue
resisting until they defeated "the criminal economic war" imposed
by the U.S.. He called it an "inhuman attempt to annihilate an
entire people through hunger and illness."
</P>
<P>
He said the parade was also in celebration of the United
Nations' rejection of a U.S. draft resolution on alleged human
rights violations in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Similar demonstrations were held in most major cities across
the island country on May Day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
