<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Minimum Salary Up 8.33 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian monthly minimum
salary rose to 130 reals (about 118 U.S. dollars) on Friday, an
8.33 percent increase over the previous minimum of 120 reals (109
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new minimum salary adjustment benefits 13 million workers,
17 percent of the economically active population of the country.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 17.7 million retired workers and pensioners will
also receive pensions equivalents to the minimum salary.
</P>
<P>
Labor Minister Edward Amadeo said the federal government
acknowledged that the new minimum salary was still low and there
were plans to increase it more, but financial restrictions
thwarted this, he added.
</P>
<P>
Amadeo said Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso kept
his promise of the presidential camplaign of 1994 to double the
minimum salary. He had adjusted the monthly minimum several times
raising it from 64 reals in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
