<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina to Return Nazi Camp Commander to Croatia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Argentina will allow the
extradition of former World War II concentration camp commander
Dinko Sakic to Croatia, where he is to face trial for war crime
charges, justice sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The former Nazi officer has told an Argentine federal judge
that he would not contest the extradition order.
</P>
<P>
Sakic was arrested Thursday in Santa Teresita town, Buenos
Aires province, after Croatia formally requested his extradition
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian government accused Sakic of committing crimes
against humanity when he headed the Jasenovac camp in Croatia
between 1942 and 1943.
</P>
<P>
About 250,000 Jews, Serbs and Gypsies died at the camp when
Sakic was commander, according to the National Institute Against
Discrimination and Xenophobia of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
Sakic was found guilty of war crimes in 1946 by a special
commission of the former Yugoslavia, but escaped to Argentina in
1947 and has lived there since.
</P>
<P>
He was identified in early April by a group of journalists
during an interview on local television. They alerted the
authorities about the presence of the alleged war criminal in
Argentina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
