<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dunhuang Police Recovers Stolen Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The Dunhuang City Public Security
Bureau has recently recovered a large cache of historical relics
pilfered from ancient tombs in the city suburbs and other areas of
northwest China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
The 133 pieces of precious relics, which date back to the
Neolithic Age, the Han Dynasty (206 B.C- A.D.220.) and the Tang
Dynasty (618-907), include stone objects, colored pottery, bronze
mirrors, painted bricks and ancient coins.
</P>
<P>
The stolen relics were confiscated from the city's craft shops
engaged in illegal sales activities. Archeologists noted that 26
relics rank as state-level historical treasures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
