<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, May 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The driver and the bodyguard of the Russian
president's envoy in Chechnya, who was kidnapped on the border
between Chechnya and Ingushetia Friday, have been arrested by the
Chechen police, the Itar-Tass news agency reported from Grozny,
capital of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
The Russian representative to Chechnya, Valentin Vlasov, on
President Boris Yeltsin's order, had attended to the Chechen
settlement in the previous government and in his former capacity
as Russian Security Council secretary, flew to Grozny Friday
evening, the report said. (Russia-Chechnya)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Friday
expressed his deep concern over the recent severe fighting between
the Tajik government forces and elements of the United Tajik
Opposition (UTO).
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Mission of Observers in Tajikistan has
reported severe fighting east of Dushanbe and within the eastern
city limits, which began Thursday. (UN-Annan-Tajikistan-Fighting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Friday
urged the United States to pay its arrears to the United Nations
without setting any preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Annan was responding to a legislation approved by the U.S.
Senate on April 28 which would provide 819 million dollars in back
U.S. dues to the United Nations. But at the same time, the
legislation sets a precondition to the payment, which imposes a
ban on any U.S. aid to international family planning groups that
lobby for abortion rights. (UN-Annan-US Arrears)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- More than 75 countries have drawn up national
environment action plans, according to the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ian Johnson, the Bank's Acting Vice President on
Environmentally and Socially Sustainable Development, told a U.N.
session here on Friday that the plans are often with the Bank's
assistance. (World Bank-Environment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on Friday signed an
emergency spending bill that would fund U.S. military operations
in the Gulf and Bosnia as well as domestic disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton criticized lawmakers, who approved the bill
Thursday night, for not including money to pay the nation's U.N.
debt and support the International Monetary
Fund. (US-Clinton-Bill)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles -- A group of Microsoft allies has warned that any
delay of Windows 98 operating system could hurt businesses and
consumers.
</P>
<P>
The claim was made in a letter to the U.S. Justice Department's
antitrust division, when federal and state regulators ponder
whether to try to delay the release of Windows 98, an upgrade of
Microsoft's dominant computer-operating
system. (US-Microsoft-Windows 98) 
</P>
</TEXT>
