<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- All the cities across the country became oceans of flowers
yesterday as Chinese regard May Day as one of the most important
festivals in the year.
</P>
<P>
Early in the morning, 3,000 model workers and a group of trade
union members from Hong Kong joined the majority of people to
watch the national flag raising ceremony in Tiananmen Square in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
In other three municipalities of Shanghai, Tianjin and
Chongqing, large numbers of festive activities were held,
including art performances, sports competitions and exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
-- Four major universities in east China's Zhejiang Province
will be merged into a new comprehensive one that will be the
largest in China. This was a significant breakthrough in China's
reform on higher education.
</P>
<P>
The gigantic Zhejiang University will consist of the present
Zhejiang University, Hangzhou University, Zhejiang Agricultural
University and Zhejiang University of Medical Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The temporary shiplock on the Three Gorges Dam on the
Yangtze River, opened to navigation at 10:00 Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
As the first major and comprehensive project after the Yangtze
River was dammed last November, the shiplock, together with a
water diversion channel, will be in use for the next six years.
</P>
<P>
-- A get-together was held in Beijing on Friday evening at the
Great Hall of the People to mark the May Day, which was attended
by more than 3,000 model workers in the country.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) and member of the CPC Central Committee Secretariat, as well
as Chairman of the All-China Federation of Trade Unions (ACFTU),
was present on the occasion.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China's economic performance this year will be better than
that of last year, said Yin Jieyan, the alternate governor of the
People's Bank of China, the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
China will meet major economic targets for 1998 such as a
growth in the gross domestic product (GDP) of 8 percent and a rise
of less than 3 percent in the consumer price index, noted Yin at a
session of the 31st annual meeting of the Asian Development Bank
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
-- A total of 166 candidates have been validly nominated for
Hong Kong's Legislative Council election on May 24, Deputy
Secretary for Constitutional Affairs Robin Ip said on Friday.
</P>
