<HEADLINE> Philippine Provincial Governor Survives Ambush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- A provincial governor who is seeking
a second term under the banner of the ruling party has survived an
assassination attempt in Surigao del Sur province, the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Daily Inquirer Saturday reported that governor Primo
Murillo were ambushed Friday morning in Lingig town by armed men
in the 26th election-related violence recorded by the police. He
survived while his four escorts were wounded.
</P>
<P>
Chief superintendent Manuel Raval, regional office director of
the Philippine National Police, said Murillo was ambushed by
members of the New People's Army, a rebel group operating in the
south.
</P>
<P>
But the ruling Lakas-NUCD party said the attempt was
"politically motivated and could have been perpetrated by the
governor's rivals in the opposition".
</P>
<P>
Sixteen candidates running for various local positions have
been killed so far in the run-up to the May 11 elections. It is
believed that more cases of violence would happen during the
election period.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992 presidential elections, at least 100 people were
killed in election-related violence. 
</P>
