<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Bangladesh Hold Joint Economic Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Commerce Minister Ishaq
Dar has underscored the need to exploit the potential for
enhancing the economic cooperation between Pakistan and
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural address during the seventh session of
Pak-Bangladesh Joint Economic Commission held here Friday, Dar
said both economies can benefit a great deal through joint
ventures in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The engineering industry in Pakistan has made significant
progress and can contribute in the development of Bangladesh's
economy, he added.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the economic agenda of the government, Dar said
that economic stability and confidence has been brought about in
the economy along with a program of structural readjustment to
revive the economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The balance of payments situation has improved, current account
deficit reduced considerably and inflation has been contained to a
single digit, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Dar urged private sectors of both countries to come forward and
play their role in promoting the bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He stressed Pakistan's desire to build a broad-based
relationship between the two South Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's Commerce Minister Tofail Ahmed said on the
occasion that the Joint Economic Commission's meeting provides an
institutional forum to pursue the goals of bilateral economic ways
and means to further expand the cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the need to have exchanges in the fields of
education and culture.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed said Bangladesh and Pakistan can focus on promoting the
activities in different sectors including banking, air traffic
insurance and shipping.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that deliberation of this meeting will
enable to identify new areas of cooperation between the two
countries. 
</P>
