to level at 8-8 and took the first four frames after the
resumption in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Doherty pulled three frames back but he was unable to end the
night on level terms. Williams produced a frame-winning break of
56 and needs just four of Saturday's nine frames to reach the
final.
</P>
<P>
After resuming at 4-4, Higgins put on a dazzling display to
end the day 12-4 ahead and needing just five more frames to win
through to his first world championship final.
</P>
<P>
Higgins will knock fellow Scotsman Stephen Hendry off the top
of the world rankings for the first time this decade if he wins
the title. 
