<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More U.S. High School Graduates Go to College </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- A record 67 percent of high
school graduates last Spring attended college in the fall as more
and more young people want to be prepared for the 21st century,
the U.S. Labor Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The need for advanced training was one factor drawing more
students into colleges, universities and community colleges, the
Department said.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that a record 70.3 percent of female high school
graduates enrolled in college, part of a longer growth trend for
women.
</P>
<P>
"I am delighted to see that more and more of our young people
see a college degree as more than just a piece of paper, but
rather as the ticket to success in the 21st Century," said Labor
Secretary Alexis M. Herman.
</P>
<P>
Of the 2.8 million members of the high school class of 1997,
nearly 1.9 million were enrolled in college. Among them, 1.7
million were enrolled full-time and nearly two-thirds were in
four-year institutions.
</P>
<P>
Of the male graduates, 63.5 percent were enrolled in college in
October 1997, a rate that could be compared to the Vietnam-era
level of 63.2 percent for men in 1968, when college enrollment was
a way to avoid the draft.
</P>
<P>
The department recorded that college enrollment of male and
female high school graduates was 54 percent and 38 percent
respectively in the 1960s. The percentages dropped in the 1970s
and remained flat in the early 1980s, but started to pick up in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The department also said that among the young people aged 16 to
24, the unemployment rate was 20 percent for those who had not
graduated from high school, compared with 11 percent for those
with a high school diploma and 2.1 percent for those with a
college degree.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
