<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Emergency Spending Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Friday signed an emergency spending bill that would fund U.S.
military operations in the Gulf and Bosnia as well as domestic
disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton criticized lawmakers, who approved the bill
Thursday night, for not including money to pay the nation's U.N.
debt and support the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
"I think we ought to pay our fair share to the IMF. I don't
care what other political business is going on in Washington,"
Clinton said from California, where he traveled to conduct some
political fund raising.
</P>
<P>
The emergency spending bill provides a total of 6 billion U.S.
dollars for the spendings.
</P>
<P>
Clinton had sent Congress the bill that also included 1 billion
dollars for back U.N. dues and 18 billion dollars for helping the
IMF to replenish loan funds depleted by the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
But because conservatives have problems with the IMF and U.N.,
Congress stripped them from the emergency legislation and will
deal with them separately.  
</P>
