<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Down Against Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, Mary 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell Friday
against a strengthening mark as the German currency benefited from
the European Union's move to name 11 countries to participate in
its new single currency.
</P>
<P>
The dollar rose against the yen as Japanese reports continued to
show a weakening economy.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the U.S. currency also was changing
hands at 1.7799 marks, down from 1.7957. The dollar was also
quoted at 133.13 yen, up from 132.72 late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the mark rallied on the belief that EU heads of
state will agree on who will be the first president of the
European central bank as well as naming the eleven member
countries to Economic and Monetary Union next year. It is
believed that former Dutch central banker Wim Duisenberg might
get the seat.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was also affected by U.S. data that indicated the
economy continued growing at a moderate pace.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, economic reports released Thursday and Friday showed a
worsening economy.
</P>
<P>
Average wages and household spending in Japan fell in March,
with salaries falling for the first time in four years, the Labor
Ministry reported.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also strengthened on reports that Japan's foreign
reserves had fallen nearly 18 billion U.S. dollars, mainly because
of intervention last month to prop up the yen.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday: 1.4890 Swiss francs, down from 1.5010; 5.9745 French
francs, down from 6.1065; 1,759.75 Italian lire, down from
1,772.45; and 1.4346 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4316.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6681 dollars, down from
1.6725 dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
