<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hepatitis C Infect Over 170 Million Worldwide: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 170 million people
worldwide have been infected by hepatitis C but no vaccine has
been available yet, said the World Health Organization (WHO) here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
It is now estimated that about 80 percent of acutely infected
patients progress to chronic hepatitis, that about 20 percent of
these chronic infections develop cirrhosis, and that one percent
to five percent of cirrhotic individuals will develop
hepatocellular carcinoma (liver cancer) during the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
To make things worse, active immunization against hepatitis C
will not be possible until early next century, WHO said in press
release issued after an expert meeting at the end of April.
</P>
<P>
Prevention efforts should include screening of all blood donors
and organ donors worldwide, informing health workers on the risk
and means of transmitting hepatitis C, educating school children
and others in the community about the disease, its effects and
means of stopping its spread, according to the experts.
</P>
<P>
In developing countries, they said, it is estimated that 90
percent of cases of hepatitis C infection are in current and
former intravenous drug users and those with a history of
transfusion of unscreened blood or blood products, such as
haemophiliacs.
</P>
<P>
The experts believed that unsterile injections and unscreened
blood are the predominant modes of transmission in developing
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
