<DOCNO> XIE19980502.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Computer Companies Back Microsoft in Windows 98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, May 1 (Xinhua) -- A group of Microsoft allies has
warned that any delay of Windows 98 operating system could hurt
businesses and consumers.
</P>
<P>
The claim was made in a letter to the U.S. Justice Department's
antitrust division, when federal and state regulators ponder
whether to try to delay the release of Windows 98, an upgrade of
Microsoft's dominant computer-operating system.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, signed by 26 computer company executives
including those of Intel, Compaq, Del and Hewlett-Packard, the
industry leaders said that many companies in the United States
have spent millions of dollars on developing, marketing and
promoting products that depend on the on-time launch of Windows
98.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft plans to ship Windows 98 to computer manufacturers in
mid-May.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft and Justice attorneys have been battling since last
October, when Justice accused the software giant of violating a
court agreement by requiring computer manufacturers to install its
Internet Explorer with Windows operating systems.
</P>
<P>
The executives said that they are not expressing an opinion on
the investigation of Microsoft. But, they said, interferring with
the release of Windows 98 would drag down the entire industry's
efforts to deliver value to customers and return to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
The letter is just one of the latest developments in the debate
whether Windows open or shut the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
In recent newspaper advertisements and meeting with the U.S.
press, Microsoft has been arguing that consumers have benefited
greatly from the constant additions to its operating system -- the
basic software that control the operation of a computer.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, Microsoft has pieced together such as a
graphical user interface, memory management, built-in networking
and multimedia support, messaging, scheduling, faxing, file and
print sharing.
</P>
<P>
It indeed benefits consumers to have a number of the features
in Windows today. But as the scope of Microsoft's "integration"
has broadened, the competitors are in the danger of being
squeezing out of the market, in which they could develop those
components and innovate.
</P>
<P>
So the competitors say that Microsoft is trying to block
innovation. But Microsoft says that the competitors could focus on
other areas to "innovate."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
