<HEADLINE> 11 Million Childhood Death Due to Environmental Factors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- In the poorest regions of the
world today, an estimated 11 million children will not live to see
their fifth birthday, primarily because of environmentally-related
diseases, such as malaria, acute respiratory infections and
diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
These are among the many sobering findings of a new report on
health and the environment worldwide, released here today jointly
by the World Resources Institute, the United Nations Environment
Program, the United Nations Development Program and the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "World Resources 1998-99", said
environmental factors are still a major cause of illness and death
in many parts of the world and children are the most at risk. 25
percent of the global burden of death and disease is due to
environmental factors. Globally 1.4 billion people are exposed to
polluted air. Infectious diseases kill 17 million and malaria is on
the rise which kills between 1 and 3 million people each year.
</P>
<P>
Leslie Roberts, Editor-in-Chief of the report, said the
developing countries suffer more severe environmental problems,
but this by no means indicates that developed countries such as
thoses in North America and Europe, have no environmental
problems. In these countries, threats stem mostly from industrial
pollutants, such as air pollutants or toxic chemicals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
