<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns of Danger of Travel to Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department on
Friday warned American tourists to be very careful when traveling
in Mexico because of a worsening crime wave.
</P>
<P>
"There certainly has been a major increase in crime in Mexico,
given the economic problems that country has faced over the last
three or four years," State Department spokesman James Foley told
a briefing.
</P>
<P>
In an updated report, the State Department warned of increasing
resentment against foreigners in the southern state of Chiapas and
advised U.S. tourists to avoid engaging in activities deemed
political by Mexican authorities.
</P>
<P>
The State Department restated its earlier warnings that
tourists should "absolutely avoid" taking any taxi that was not
summoned or contracted in advance.
</P>
<P>
In March, a former Yale University art instructor, Carol Janet
Schlosberg, 30, was raped and murdered on a beach in Puerto
Escondido, a resort in the southern state of Oaxaca.
</P>
<P>
The State Department said it did not expect the travel warning
to hurt the tourism industry in Mexico, the United States' second
most important trading partner.
</P>
<P>
"If you have 20 million Americans visiting that country, it
would be a tall order to make a very big dent in those kind of
figures," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
"Mexico obviously remains a very attractive tourist destination
to Americans," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
